# Introducing 'Else'

A single `if` statement is great for running code only when a condition is true. But what if we want to run *different* code when it's false?

Enter the **`else`** statement. It acts as the default "catch-all" or backup plan.

```javascript
let score = 50;

if (score >= 100) {
  console.log("You Win!"); // Runs if true
} else {
  console.log("You Lose!"); // Runs if false
}
```

Unlike `if`, the `else` block **does not have a condition ()** because it simply runs when the `if` fails.

slides.codeSnippet:
let password = "wrongpass";

if (password === "secret123") {
  console.log("Access Granted 🔓");
} else {
  console.log("Access Denied 🔒");
}

slides.content:
## Testing Multiple Conditions

Sometimes, a simple yes/no isn't enough. We might have 3, 4, or 5 different outcomes!

We can chain conditions together using **`else if`**.

```javascript
let grade = 85;

if (grade >= 90) {
  console.log("A");
} else if (grade >= 80) {
  console.log("B"); // This runs!
} else if (grade >= 70) {
  console.log("C");
} else {
  console.log("F"); // The final backup
}
```

**Important Info:** JavaScript checks these from **top to bottom**. As soon as it finds the FIRST true condition, it runs that block and **skips everything else**!

slides.codeSnippet:
let timeOfDay = 14; // Military time, 2pm

if (timeOfDay < 12) {
  console.log("Good Morning! 🌅");
} else if (timeOfDay < 17) {
  console.log("Good Afternoon! ☀️");
} else {
  console.log("Good Evening! 🌙");
}

slides.content:
## Top-to-Bottom Execution

Because JavaScript stops at the **first true condition**, the order of your `else if` statements is CRITICAL.

Look at this flawed grading code:

```javascript
let grade = 95;

// Bad Code!
if (grade >= 70) {
  console.log("C"); 
} else if (grade >= 90) {
  console.log("A");
} 
```

Even though 95 is an A, this code will print "C"! Since 95 is indeed `>= 70`, the first block triggers and the rest of the checking is aborted. Always order your checks carefully! 🧱
